<DOC><DOCNO> AP900208-0145 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-02-08-90 1657EST</FILEID><FIRST>r w AM-Quayle-BreastCancer     02-08 0286</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Quayle-Breast Cancer,280</SECOND><HEAD>Quayles Kick Off Breast Cancer Awareness Campaign</HEAD><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Vice President Dan Quayle joined his wifeMarilyn on Thursday to kick off a $400,000 campaign to raise publicawareness about preventing breast cancer, stating, ``It's notsolely a woman's issue.''   The Quayles and Health and Human Services Secretary LouisSullivan announced they will participate in a June 16five-kilometer run to raise money for breast cancer research andtreatment.   ``As terrible as this disease is, it is treatable through earlydetection,'' the vice president said at a news conference.   Quayle joined the effort at the urging of his wife, whose motherdied of breast cancer at age 56.   ``When breast cancer kills 40,000 women each year, it becomes anissue for every family, every community, and yes, the nationbecomes concerned,'' Quayle said. ``The health issue affects somany Americans that it is not solely a women's issue.''   ``We are committed to make a difference,'' he said.   The Quayles will be chairmen of the June 16 ``Race for theCure'' in Washington to raise money for breast cancer research andtreatment. The fund-raising goal for the event is $400,000, withthe money to go for low-cost mammograms for women in Washington andto support the Susan G. Komen Foundation which funds research,education and treatment of breast cancer.   Sullivan and several members of Congress as well as celebritiesLynda Carter, Loni Anderson and Larry Hagman also will join therace.   The Quayles plan to produce a series of public serviceannouncements to raise public awareness about the importance ofearly detection, and Mrs. Quayle said her husband will make publicappearances around the country to highlight cancer detection andtreatment programs.</TEXT></DOC>